Double-check render layer / mask mismatch

If your catalog / materials use a custom layer for Entities Graphics (quite common), you can end up rendering only to a layer the camera doesn’t see.

Agents – verify & enforce:

Check RenderFilterSettings (if used) in catalog / authoring:

If your Space4XRenderCatalogAuthoring or catalog asset sets a custom RenderFilterSettings.RenderLayerMask, ensure it uses a layer the camera actually renders.

Easiest: temporarily use default:

// wherever RenderFilterSettings are created for carriers
renderFilterSettings.RenderLayer = RenderLayer.Default;


Camera culling mask:

Make sure the active Camera’s Culling Mask includes the layer that ECS entities are on.

For now, set it to Everything in the inspector as a sanity check.

3. Prove the mesh/material in the catalog are valid

Right now DebugVerifyVisualsSystem shows RenderBounds but not what mesh/material the catalog is actually providing. We want to be 100% sure ArchetypeId=200 is mapped to a visible mesh and material.

Agents – extend DebugVerifyVisualsSystem to log mesh/material:

Inside OnUpdate, after you retrieve RenderKey + MaterialMeshInfo, also pull from Space4XRenderMeshArraySingleton:

using Unity.Rendering;

public partial struct DebugVerifyVisualsSystem : ISystem
{
    public void OnUpdate(ref SystemState state)
    {
        var rmaSingleton = SystemAPI.GetSingleton<Space4XRenderMeshArraySingleton>();
        var rma = rmaSingleton.RenderMeshArray; // adjust to your field name

        foreach (var (rk, mmi, entity) in
                 SystemAPI.Query<RefRO<RenderKey>, RefRO<MaterialMeshInfo>>()
                          .WithEntityAccess())
        {
            var index = mmi.ValueRO.MaterialMeshIndex;
            var mesh  = rma.GetMesh(index);
            var mat   = rma.GetMaterial(index);

            UnityEngine.Debug.Log(
                $"[DebugVerifyVisualsSystem] e={entity} ArchetypeId={rk.ValueRO.ArchetypeId} " +
                $"Index={index} Mesh={(mesh ? mesh.name : \"<null>\")} " +
                $"Mat={(mat ? mat.name : \"<null>\")}"
            );
            break; // just dump first one for now
        }
    }
}


If you see:

Mesh=<null> or Mat=<null> → catalog entry for the carrier archetype is broken.
Fix: in Space4XRenderCatalogAuthoring’s inspector, ensure the carrier entry references a visible mesh & opaque material.

A valid mesh/material name → catalog is good; the problem is not assets.

